Note: ============================================================================
Note: BuildContext Layout (mirrors build_system.runa)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: BuildContext field offsets used by this module. Authoritative
Note: layout lives in build_system.runa lines 73-97 (192-byte struct).
Note: optimization_level: Integer at offset 16 (BUILD_OPT_* values).
Note: target_triple: String pointer at offset 24 (e.g. "x86_64-linux-gnu").
Note: arena: Pointer at offset 56 (owns the BuildContext and its children).
Constant BUILDCTX_OPTIMIZATION_LEVEL_OFFSET as Integer is 16
Constant BUILDCTX_TARGET_TRIPLE_OFFSET as Integer is 24
Constant BUILDCTX_ARENA_OFFSET as Integer is 56

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Module-Global: Active BuildContext
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Shared module-global storing the active BuildContext pointer for the
duration of a compile_program invocation. Per design v3 section 19.6
option 3 (CEO-ratified): every worker in a parallel build sets this
to the same shared pool BuildContext pointer, so the write is
idempotent and concurrent worker writes are benign.

The bootstrap compiler's verified working module-global idiom is a
top-level `Let X be 0` directly followed by Processes that read/write
it. This mirrors the existing `global_compiler_context_ptr` pattern in
whole_program_analysis.runa lines 4198-4200.
@End Reasoning

Note: File-local static cell for the active BuildContext pointer.
Note: Set by set_active_build_context, read by get_active_opt_level.
Let active_build_context_ptr be 0

Note: ============================================================================
Note: P2-D D-FFI-09 — FFI Library Collector
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Module-global list of unique library names discovered while compiling. Each
Note: HIR_EXTERNAL_DECLARATION node carries a library_name field at offset 120
Note: identifying the C-side library; the orchestrator scans these and appends
Note: unique names to this list. The link step consumes the list and invokes
Note: linker_driver_add_library for each, after platform-aware translation.
Note: Per Q1 ratification, default link_type is dynamic. Per CEO no-defer
Note: directive, the orchestrator collects libraries from EVERY External
Note: declaration regardless of link_type — the runtime resolver handles
Note: dynamic resolution, the static linker handles static.
Let ffi_libraries_collected be 0
Note: ffi_libraries_collected holds a List pointer once populated.
Note: ffi_objc_present is 1 if any objc-convention External was seen.
Let ffi_objc_present be 0
Note: ffi_target_os_active is the active target OS during compile_program
Note: (mirrored from get_target_os_from_config so link helpers can read it).
Let ffi_target_os_active be 0
Note: ffi_frameworks_collected holds a List pointer once populated. Mirrors
Note: ffi_libraries_collected but for Darwin `from framework "Name"` declarations.
Note: Frameworks are tracked separately from libraries because the linker
Note: surface differs ("-framework Name" vs "-lname") and dedup is per-framework
Note: rather than per-library — declaring an External Process from framework
Note: "Foundation" and another from library "c" must produce both a -lc flag
Note: and a -framework Foundation flag, not a merged single -l/-framework entry.
Let ffi_frameworks_collected be 0

Process called "ffi_get_collected_libraries" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Public accessor for the module-global FFI library collector List.
    Consumed by linker_driver_link to register every required library
    against the LinkerContext before the link step runs. Returns 0
    (rather than an empty List) when no FFI declarations have been
    seen, which the consumer treats as "no FFI libraries to register".
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single read of the module-global pointer cell. Stateless.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). One load. Called once per link.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Read-only accessor. The returned List pointer is shared with the
    linker driver; the linker driver only reads from it (uses size/get
    only, never mutates) so concurrent collector population from
    parallel compile workers is safe under the worker-completes-before-link
    barrier the build system enforces.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return ffi_libraries_collected
End Process

Process called "ffi_has_objc_external" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Public accessor for the objc-presence flag. Returns 1 if any
    objc-convention External was encountered by ffi_scan_hir_program_for_externals
    during the current compile, 0 otherwise. The linker driver uses this
    to gate the Darwin-target validation per CEO Q3.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single read of the module-global pointer cell. Stateless.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). One load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Read-only accessor. A false negative (returning 0 when objc was
    present) would bypass the Q3 platform check and let the linker
    fail later with a less-informative unresolved-symbol error; the
    setter ffi_mark_objc_present is the only mutator and is called
    by the trusted HIR-scan path.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return ffi_objc_present
End Process

Process called "ffi_get_active_target_os" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Public accessor for the active target OS captured during
    compile_program's Phase 3a (FFI library collection). The linker
    driver reads this to drive platform-aware library translation and
    objc-target validation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single read of the module-global pointer cell. Returns the OS_*
    identifier (mirror of MachineCode TARGET_OS_* values).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). One load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Read-only accessor. The OS identifier flows from the trusted target
    configuration; user FFI code cannot reach this surface.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return ffi_target_os_active
End Process

Process called "ffi_get_collected_frameworks" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Public accessor for the module-global FFI framework collector List.
    Consumed by linker_driver_link to register every required Darwin
    framework against the LinkerContext before the link step runs.
    Returns 0 (rather than an empty List) when no framework-bearing
    External declarations have been seen, which the consumer treats as
    "no FFI frameworks to register".
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single read of the module-global pointer cell. Stateless.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). One load. Called once per link.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Read-only accessor. The returned List pointer is shared with the
    linker driver; the linker driver only reads from it (uses size/get
    only, never mutates) so concurrent collector population from parallel
    compile workers is safe under the worker-completes-before-link
    barrier the build system enforces.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return ffi_frameworks_collected
End Process

Process called "ffi_register_framework" takes framework_name as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Appends a framework name to the FFI framework collector list with
    deduplication. Called by ffi_scan_hir_program_for_externals for each
    HIR_EXTERNAL_DECLARATION that carries a non-zero framework_name at
    HIR offset 128. Deduplication is essential because Darwin programs
    commonly declare many External Processes from the same framework
    (Foundation, AppKit, UIKit) and the linker prefers one -framework
    flag per framework even though duplicates are accepted.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Lazily allocates the collector list on first call. Walks the existing
    entries with proc size and proc get from List, comparing each via
    string_equals; on a match returns 0 to indicate the name was already
    present (caller treats this as a no-op success). Otherwise appends
    and returns 1. Returns 0 for a null framework_name.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(n) in the current collector size. For typical Darwin Runa programs
    n is at most a handful (Foundation, CoreFoundation, AppKit), so each
    call is at most a few hundred nanoseconds. Total cost per compile is
    O(n * declarations) which is well-bounded.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Framework names flow from user source code through the parser and
    HIR builder. The collector here does not sanitize; downstream
    linker_driver_add_framework performs the security validation against
    the linker's input grammar. String_equals compares contents, not
    pointers, so the deduplication is correct even when separate parses
    produce distinct string allocations for the same framework name.
    @End Security_Scope

    If framework_name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ffi_frameworks_collected is equal to 0:
        Set ffi_frameworks_collected to proc create from List
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with ffi_frameworks_collected
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let existing be proc get from List with ffi_frameworks_collected, i
        Let is_dup be proc string_equals from StringCore with existing, framework_name
        If is_dup is equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc append from List with ffi_frameworks_collected, framework_name
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ffi_clear_collected_libraries" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resets the FFI library collector and related flags between builds.
    Called at the start of each compile-and-link cycle so that
    libraries / objc presence / target OS from the previous build do
    not leak into the next. Essential for the parallel-compilation path
    where a single process handles many compile jobs in sequence.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Four single-word stores: library collector list to 0 (the consumer's
    "no FFI libraries" sentinel), framework collector list to 0 (same
    sentinel for the framework consumer), objc-presence to 0, target_os
    to 0. The collector list pointers are dropped rather than freed;
    if the previous build's lists survive via shared reference (e.g.,
    for debugging), they remain accessible to those holders. The next
    ffi_register_library / ffi_register_framework call lazily allocates
    a fresh list.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Four stores. Cold path -- called once per build.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Reset semantics prevent stale state from one build (e.g., objc
    presence, prior-target frameworks) from leaking into the next, which
    is a correctness requirement for multi-target build orchestrators
    that switch target OS between builds. No memory is freed; callers
    that retain pointers to the previous lists assume responsibility for
    their lifetime.
    @End Security_Scope

    Set ffi_libraries_collected to 0
    Set ffi_frameworks_collected to 0
    Set ffi_objc_present to 0
    Set ffi_target_os_active to 0
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ffi_register_library" takes lib_name as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Appends a library name to the FFI collector list with deduplication.
    Called by ffi_scan_hir_program_for_externals for each
    HIR_EXTERNAL_DECLARATION encountered. Deduplication is essential
    because most real programs declare many External Processes from
    the same library (libc, pthread) and the linker tolerates duplicate
    -l flags but the diagnostic output is cleaner without them.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Lazily allocates the collector list on first call. Walks the
    existing entries with proc size + proc get from List, comparing
    each via string_equals; on a match returns 0 to indicate the name
    was already present (caller treats this as a no-op success).
    Otherwise appends and returns 1. Returns 0 for a null lib_name.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(n) in the current collector size. For typical Runa programs
    n <= 5, so each call is at most a few hundred nanoseconds. Total
    cost per compile is O(n * declarations) which is well-bounded.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Library names flow from user source code through the parser and
    HIR builder. The collector here does not sanitize; downstream
    linker_driver_add_library performs the security validation against
    the linker's input grammar. String_equals compares contents, not
    pointers, so the deduplication is correct even when separate parses
    produce distinct string allocations for the same library name.
    @End Security_Scope

    If lib_name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ffi_libraries_collected is equal to 0:
        Set ffi_libraries_collected to proc create from List
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with ffi_libraries_collected
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let existing be proc get from List with ffi_libraries_collected, i
        Let is_dup be proc string_equals from StringCore with existing, lib_name
        If is_dup is equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc append from List with ffi_libraries_collected, lib_name
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ffi_mark_objc_present" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Sets the module-global flag indicating that at least one
    objc-convention External was encountered during the current
    compile. Called by ffi_scan_hir_program_for_externals when it sees
    a convention_id == 5 at offset 152 of an HIR_EXTERNAL_DECLARATION
    node. The linker driver reads the flag at link time to enforce the
    Q3 Darwin-only target constraint.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single store to 1. Idempotent -- subsequent calls are no-ops.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). One store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Setter for a security-relevant flag (drives Q3 platform check). Only
    the trusted HIR-scan path invokes this Process; user code cannot
    reach it directly.
    @End Security_Scope

    Set ffi_objc_present to 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ffi_scan_hir_program_for_externals" takes hir_program as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Walks the HIR program's top-level declarations and registers each
    HIR_EXTERNAL_DECLARATION's library name and framework name with the
    FFI library and framework collectors. Also detects objc-convention
    externals for link-time platform validation.

    Per D-FFI-09 (P2-D), this gives the linker driver a complete list of
    libraries and frameworks to bind at link time without requiring
    per-file boilerplate on the user side.

    A1 amendment (subsystem audit follow-up): framework_name at HIR
    offset 128 is now read and routed to ffi_register_framework so that
    Darwin `from framework "Foundation"` declarations produce a real
    `-framework Foundation` linker entry rather than being silently
    dropped after parse.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Each HIR program node holds children at offset 24. Each child is
    checked for node_type == HIR_EXTERNAL_DECLARATION (12004); if matched:
      - library_name at offset 120 is registered via ffi_register_library
        when non-zero.
      - framework_name at offset 128 is registered via
        ffi_register_framework when non-zero (Darwin path).
      - convention_id at offset 152 == 5 (objc) sets the global
        objc-presence flag via ffi_mark_objc_present.

    Library and framework registration are independent: a single External
    declaration may carry both a library_name and a framework_name (the
    library form is used on POSIX targets while the framework form is
    used on Darwin), and both must be tracked.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(n) over the declaration list with two list-walk lookups per
    matching HIR_EXTERNAL_DECLARATION (one in ffi_register_library, one
    in ffi_register_framework when framework_name is set). Typical
    programs declare a small fixed number of externals; total scan cost
    is on the order of microseconds even for large codebases.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Reads only from the HIR node memory layout via fixed offsets. All
    consumed pointer values are passed to ffi_register_library /
    ffi_register_framework / ffi_mark_objc_present which perform their
    own null checks and deduplication. No user data reaches a security-
    sensitive surface from this Process directly.
    @End Security_Scope

    If hir_program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let decls be __load(hir_program, 24)
    If decls is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc size from List with decls
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc get from List with decls, i
        If decl is not equal to 0:
            Let decl_type be __load(decl, 0)
            If decl_type is equal to 12004:
                Note: HIR_EXTERNAL_DECLARATION
                Let lib_name be __load(decl, 120)
                If lib_name is not equal to 0:
                    ffi_register_library(lib_name)
                End If
                Let framework_name be __load(decl, 128)
                If framework_name is not equal to 0:
                    ffi_register_framework(framework_name)
                End If
                Let conv_id be __load(decl, 152)
                If conv_id is equal to 5:
                    ffi_mark_objc_present()
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "set_active_build_context" that takes ctx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stores the supplied BuildContext pointer in the module-global slot
    so subsequent compile_program calls within the same build can read
    opt_level (and any future BuildContext-derived knobs) without
    threading the context through the call chain. Every caller in the
    driver layer (build_system, parallel_compilation) invokes this
    once before its compile_program call. The shared-cell write is
    idempotent across workers in a build because every worker writes
    the same pointer value (Q1 option 3).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single-word write to the module-global cell. The bootstrap
    compiler treats the top-level `Let active_build_context_ptr be 0`
    as a static-storage cell; Set writes through to it. Returns 1
    unconditionally to indicate the write was performed.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single pointer store. Inlined by the optimizer at -O2.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Stored pointer is opaque to this module; only
    the field at BUILDCTX_OPTIMIZATION_LEVEL_OFFSET is read back.
    @End Security_Scope

    Set active_build_context_ptr to ctx
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_active_opt_level" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resolves the active optimization level for the current
    compile_program invocation. If a BuildContext was set via
    set_active_build_context, reads
    BUILDCTX_OPTIMIZATION_LEVEL_OFFSET from it. Otherwise returns
    BUILD_OPT_BASIC (=O1), the Q3-ratified default for the legacy
    single-file driver path that has no BuildContext.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the module-global pointer. If null, return BUILD_OPT_BASIC.
    Otherwise dereference at offset 16. Clamp the result so a
    corrupted BuildContext cannot push the backend into an undefined
    opt_level branch.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two pointer dereferences on the BuildContext path; one constant
    return on the default path. Inlined by the optimizer at -O2.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Read-only access to the BuildContext field.
    @End Security_Scope

    If active_build_context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return BUILD_OPT_BASIC
    End If
    Let level be __load(active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_OPTIMIZATION_LEVEL_OFFSET)
    Note: Clamp to valid range so a corrupted context cannot push the
    Note: backend into an undefined opt_level branch.
    If level is less than BUILD_OPT_NONE_LOCAL:
        Return BUILD_OPT_BASIC
    End If
    If level is greater than BUILD_OPT_AGGRESSIVE_LOCAL:
        Return BUILD_OPT_AGGRESSIVE_LOCAL
    End If
    Return level
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Target Resolution Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "map_tm_os_to_machine_code_os" that takes tm_os as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The TargetManager parser emits OS identifiers in its own encoding
    (target_manager.runa lines 70-84) which differs from the MachineCode
    TARGET_OS_* encoding consumed by create_backend_config and
    create_convention_for_target. This helper performs the lossless
    mapping from TargetManager values to MachineCode values for the
    OS dimensions that have machine_code support.

    OSes that TargetManager recognises but MachineCode cannot target
    (Dragonfly, iOS, Android, Fuchsia, Haiku, Serenity, Redox, bare
    none) map to OS_LINUX so codegen still produces a well-formed
    System V ELF object. This is the conservative behavior: the
    backend is correct for unsupported targets even though the host
    platform identity may not match.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Branch on the TargetManager OS value. Direct mapping for the seven
    supported OSes (Linux, Windows, macOS->Darwin, FreeBSD, OpenBSD,
    NetBSD, none->bare-metal). All other values fall through to the
    conservative Linux default.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pure value-to-value mapping; no allocations. Inlined at O2.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. No external inputs.
    @End Security_Scope

    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_LINUX:
        Return TARGET_OS_LINUX from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_WINDOWS:
        Return TARGET_OS_WINDOWS from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_MACOS:
        Return TARGET_OS_DARWIN from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_FREEBSD:
        Return TARGET_OS_FREEBSD from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_OPENBSD:
        Return TARGET_OS_OPENBSD from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_NETBSD:
        Return TARGET_OS_NETBSD from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_NONE:
        Return TARGET_OS_BARE_METAL from MachineCode
    End If
    Return TARGET_OS_LINUX from MachineCode
End Process

Process called "map_tm_arch_to_machine_code_arch" that takes tm_arch as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Mirrors map_tm_os_to_machine_code_os for the architecture dimension.
    TargetManager (target_manager.runa lines 56-67) and MachineCode
    (machine_code_interface.runa lines 43-53) disagree on the integer
    encoding for several architectures (notably MIPS slots and the
    POWERPC unification). This helper performs the precise mapping.

    Both encoders cover the same arch set, so this mapping is total:
    every TargetManager arch resolves to a MachineCode arch. The
    POWERPC32/POWERPC64 split on the TargetManager side collapses to
    a single ARCH_POWERPC on the MachineCode side (the backend uses
    pointer-size to disambiguate).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Branch on the TargetManager arch value. The eleven arches map
    directly except: TM POWERPC64 and TM POWERPC32 both collapse to
    MachineCode ARCH_POWERPC (backend disambiguates via config bits).
    Unknown values fall through to ARCH_X86_64 as the conservative
    host-platform default for v0.0.8.5 (Linux x86_64 production).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pure value-to-value mapping; no allocations. Inlined at O2.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. No external inputs.
    @End Security_Scope

    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_X86_64:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_X86_64 from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_AARCH64:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_AARCH64 from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_ARM32:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_ARM32 from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_RISCV64:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_RISCV64 from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_RISCV32:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_RISCV32 from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_MIPS64:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_MIPS64 from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_MIPS32:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_MIPS32 from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_POWERPC64:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_POWERPC from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_POWERPC32:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_POWERPC from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_WASM32:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_WASM32 from MachineCode
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_WASM64:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_WASM64 from MachineCode
    End If
    Return TARGET_ARCH_X86_64 from MachineCode
End Process

Process called "get_target_os_from_config" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resolves the target OS for codegen from the active BuildContext.
    BuildContext stores the user-supplied target as a triple string
    (e.g. "x86_64-linux-gnu") at offset BUILDCTX_TARGET_TRIPLE_OFFSET;
    the orchestrator parses that string via TargetManager and converts
    the resulting OS identifier into the MachineCode TARGET_OS_*
    encoding that create_backend_config and
    create_convention_for_target consume.

    The no-context path and the empty-triple path both fall back to
    OS_LINUX, which matches get_default_target's host-platform answer
    on the v0.0.8.5 production Linux host. The unknown-OS path also
    falls back to OS_LINUX so an unparseable triple still produces a
    well-formed Linux build instead of failing codegen.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-tier resolution:
      1. No active BuildContext -> OS_LINUX (host default).
      2. BuildContext present but target_triple field is 0 (empty,
         the create_build_context default per build_system.runa:137)
         -> OS_LINUX.
      3. target_triple present -> parse via TargetManager using the
         BuildContext's own arena (offset BUILDCTX_ARENA_OFFSET) for
         the transient TargetTriple struct, extract os via
         get_target_os, then translate from TargetManager's OS
         encoding to the MachineCode TARGET_OS_* encoding via
         map_tm_os_to_machine_code_os.

    The transient TargetTriple lives in the BuildContext's arena and
    is reclaimed when the build's arena_destroy fires; no per-call
    teardown required.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path on multi-file builds: called once per compile_program
    invocation. Triple parsing is O(triple_length) and allocates a
    72-byte TargetTriple in the build arena. For repeated
    invocations against the same triple, the cost is dominated by
    arena_allocate; inlining at O2 collapses the dispatch overhead.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Reads from a build-supplied target_triple
    string; parser validates the format and rejects malformed input
    via OS_UNKNOWN, which the mapper folds to OS_LINUX.
    @End Security_Scope

    If active_build_context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return TARGET_OS_LINUX from MachineCode
    End If
    Let triple_string be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_TARGET_TRIPLE_OFFSET
    If triple_string is equal to 0:
        Return TARGET_OS_LINUX from MachineCode
    End If
    Let arena be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_ARENA_OFFSET
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return TARGET_OS_LINUX from MachineCode
    End If
    Let triple be proc parse_target_triple from TargetManager with arena, triple_string
    If triple is equal to 0:
        Return TARGET_OS_LINUX from MachineCode
    End If
    Let tm_os be proc get_target_os from TargetManager with triple
    Return map_tm_os_to_machine_code_os(tm_os)
End Process

Process called "get_target_arch_from_config" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resolves the target architecture for codegen from the active
    BuildContext. Same resolution shape as get_target_os_from_config:
    parse the BuildContext's target_triple string via TargetManager,
    extract the arch identifier, then translate from TargetManager's
    arch encoding to the MachineCode TARGET_ARCH_* encoding that
    create_backend_config and dispatch_codegen_by_arch consume.

    Both functions resolve from the same BuildContext field, so on
    builds where compile_program calls both helpers consecutively the
    second call re-parses the triple. parse_target_triple is cheap
    (sub-microsecond, single arena alloc) so the duplication is
    acceptable in exchange for keeping the two helpers independent
    and stateless.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-tier resolution mirrored from get_target_os_from_config:
      1. No active BuildContext -> ARCH_X86_64 (host default).
      2. target_triple field is 0 -> ARCH_X86_64.
      3. Otherwise parse the triple, call get_target_arch, and run
         the result through map_tm_arch_to_machine_code_arch to
         produce a MachineCode TARGET_ARCH_* value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost profile as get_target_os_from_config. Inlining at O2
    fuses the two helpers' parses when both are called in the same
    invocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Parser rejects malformed triples via
    ARCH_UNKNOWN, which the mapper folds to ARCH_X86_64.
    @End Security_Scope

    If active_build_context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_X86_64 from MachineCode
    End If
    Let triple_string be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_TARGET_TRIPLE_OFFSET
    If triple_string is equal to 0:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_X86_64 from MachineCode
    End If
    Let arena be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_ARENA_OFFSET
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_X86_64 from MachineCode
    End If
    Let triple be proc parse_target_triple from TargetManager with arena, triple_string
    If triple is equal to 0:
        Return TARGET_ARCH_X86_64 from MachineCode
    End If
    Let tm_arch be proc get_target_arch from TargetManager with triple
    Return map_tm_arch_to_machine_code_arch(tm_arch)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Source-File Tagging
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "derive_input_name_from_output" that takes output_path as Integer, arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The merged-AST source-file tagging step needs the input filename
    so codegen can disambiguate same-named structs from different
    source files. Convention: output paths produced by the v0.0.8.5
    driver substitute ".s" for ".runa". This helper reverses that
    transformation. If the output path does not end in ".s" we return
    the output path unchanged so callers can still tag functions with
    a stable, non-null source-file pointer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Compute the length of output_path; allocate a buffer of equal
    capacity in the per-job arena; copy bytes, then strip ".s" suffix
    if present and append ".runa". The arena owns the returned
    buffer so no manual deallocation is required.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Called once per compile_program invocation. O(n) in path length.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Pure transformation; no filesystem touch.
    @End Security_Scope

    If output_path is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compute string length via the StringCore primitive.
    Let path_len be proc string_length from StringCore with output_path
    If path_len is less than 1:
        Return output_path
    End If

    Note: Allocate destination buffer in the per-job arena. Use the
    Note: layout arena_allocate primitive if available, falling back
    Note: to the runtime allocator if arena is 0.
    Let buf_size be path_len plus 8
    Let buf be 0
    If arena is not equal to 0:
        Set buf to proc arena_allocate from Layout with arena, buf_size
    End If
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Set buf to proc allocate from Layout with buf_size
    End If
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return output_path
    End If

    Note: Detect ".s" suffix.
    Let copy_len be path_len
    Let has_s_suffix be 0
    If path_len is greater than or equal to 2:
        Let suffix_a be __load_byte(output_path, path_len minus 2)
        Let suffix_b be __load_byte(output_path, path_len minus 1)
        If suffix_a is equal to 46:
            If suffix_b is equal to 115:
                Set has_s_suffix to 1
                Set copy_len to path_len minus 2
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Copy the prefix.
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than copy_len:
        Let b be __load_byte(output_path, i)
        __store_byte(buf, i, b)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Append ".runa" then NUL.
    If has_s_suffix is equal to 1:
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len, 46)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 1, 114)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 2, 117)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 3, 110)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 4, 97)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 5, 0)
    Otherwise:
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len, 0)
    End If

    Return buf
End Process

Process called "function_get_source_file" that takes func as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reads the source-file path pointer stored on a legacy-layout Function
    record. The v0.0.8.4.5 parser stores the path at byte offset 48 of
    each Function (FUNCTION_SOURCE_FILE_OFFSET in its parser.runa); these
    accessors replicate that contract locally so compile_program links
    against the v0.0.8.5 runtime without dragging in the legacy parser
    object. Returns 0 for functions that were never tagged (for example
    compiler-synthesized __module_init bodies); callers must treat 0 as
    "unknown".
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Null-check func, then read the pointer at offset 48 via MemoryCore.
    @End Implementation

    If func is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with func, 48
End Process

Process called "function_set_source_file" that takes func as Integer, file_path as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stamps the source-file path pointer onto a legacy-layout Function
    record at byte offset 48. The passed pointer is stored as-is; the
    caller is responsible for keeping the string alive for the lifetime
    of the program (the output-path-derived input filename allocated by
    compile_program satisfies this).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Null-check func, then write the pointer at offset 48 via MemoryCore.
    Returns 1 on success, 0 on null func.
    @End Implementation

    If func is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_pointer from MemoryCore with func, 48, file_path
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "type_definition_get_source_file" that takes type_def as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reads the source-file path pointer stored on a legacy-layout
    TypeDefinition record. The v0.0.8.4.5 parser stores the path at byte
    offset 48 (TYPEDEFINITION_SOURCE_FILE_OFFSET in its parser.runa).
    Returns 0 for untagged type definitions; callers treat 0 as "unknown".
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Null-check type_def, then read the pointer at offset 48 via MemoryCore.
    @End Implementation

    If type_def is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with type_def, 48
End Process

Process called "type_definition_set_source_file" that takes type_def as Integer, file_path as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stamps the source-file path pointer onto a legacy-layout
    TypeDefinition record at byte offset 48, mirroring
    function_set_source_file for type records.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Null-check type_def, then write the pointer at offset 48 via
    MemoryCore. Returns 1 on success, 0 on null type_def.
    @End Implementation

    If type_def is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_pointer from MemoryCore with type_def, 48, file_path
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "tag_source_files_in_program" that takes program as Integer, source_name as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The caller's process_imports path merges imported functions/types
    into the main AST and tags each with its origin source file. The
    main program's own functions/types may have been left with a null
    source_file pointer (the v0.0.8.4.5 parser does not set it
    eagerly). This helper walks the merged AST and re-stamps any
    function or type whose source_file is null, using the
    output-path-derived input filename. This mirrors the safety net
    in v0.0.8.4.5.3.5 main.runa lines 319-350.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read function_count at PROGRAM offset 8 and functions array at
    offset 0. Iterate; for each function whose source_file
    (function_get_source_file) is null, call
    function_set_source_file(func, source_name). Repeat for types at
    offsets 40 (types pointer) and 32 (count). The
    function_set_source_file and function_get_source_file Processes
    are defined locally in this module against the legacy Function/
    TypeDefinition layout (source_file pointer at byte offset 48).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(F + T) where F = function count, T = type count in the
    program. Called once per compile_program invocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Writes pointers into AST nodes; no external
    data accessed.
    @End Security_Scope

    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If source_name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Functions.
    Let func_count be proc memory_get_int32 from MemoryCore with program, 8
    Let funcs_array be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with program, 0
    If funcs_array is not equal to 0:
        Let fi be 0
        While fi is less than func_count:
            Let func_off be fi multiplied by 8
            Let func_ptr be funcs_array plus func_off
            Let func be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with func_ptr, 0
            If func is not equal to 0:
                Let existing be function_get_source_file(func)
                If existing is equal to 0:
                    function_set_source_file(func, source_name)
                End If
            End If
            Set fi to fi plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Types.
    Let type_count be proc memory_get_int32 from MemoryCore with program, 32
    Let types_array be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with program, 40
    If types_array is not equal to 0:
        Let ti be 0
        While ti is less than type_count:
            Let type_off be ti multiplied by 8
            Let type_ptr be types_array plus type_off
            Let type_def be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with type_ptr, 0
            If type_def is not equal to 0:
                Let existing_t be type_definition_get_source_file(type_def)
                If existing_t is equal to 0:
                    type_definition_set_source_file(type_def, source_name)
                End If
            End If
            Set ti to ti plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Per-Architecture Codegen Dispatcher
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dispatch_codegen_by_arch" that takes target_arch as Integer, lir_module as Integer, backend_config as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wires the LIR module to one of the seven v0.0.8.5 architecture
    backends. Per CEO directive (Q4 of design v3), every existing
    arch generator is wired here -- no "fallback raises error" branch
    is permitted because such a fallback renders the un-wired generators
    orphans. Two calling-convention shapes are handled:

    1. Direct shape (lir_module, config) -> AssemblyOutput*
       x86_64, aarch64, arm32, riscv64, riscv32

    2. Context shape (ctx, lir_module) -> Integer where
       ctx = create_<arch>_asm_context(output, config)
       mips64, mips32, powerpc, wasm32, wasm64

    For the context-shape backends, the dispatcher creates the
    AssemblyOutput and per-arch context here so the generator can be
    invoked uniformly. Both paths return an AssemblyOutput pointer
    that asm_finalize then converts to text.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Branch on target_arch. For direct-shape backends, forward to the
    arch entry point. For context-shape backends, allocate a fresh
    AssemblyOutput via create_assembly_output, build the per-arch
    context, run the generator, then return the AssemblyOutput
    pointer. The arena pointer threaded into create_assembly_output
    is the per-job arena passed in via the backend_config's
    underlying state; if no arena is reachable we fall back to the
    runtime allocator.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Eleven-way branch on a single integer. The architect-recommended
    branch order places x86_64 first (the production path) to
    minimize branch overhead in the common case.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. The dispatcher does not validate the
    lir_module shape; that is the LIR builder's responsibility.
    @End Security_Scope

    If lir_module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If backend_config is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Direct-shape: x86_64 (production primary).
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_X86_64 from MachineCode:
        Let x86_out be proc generate_x86_64_assembly from X86Gen with lir_module, backend_config
        Return x86_out
    End If

    Note: Direct-shape: aarch64.
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_AARCH64 from MachineCode:
        Let arm64_out be proc generate_aarch64_assembly from ARM64Gen with lir_module, backend_config
        Return arm64_out
    End If

    Note: Direct-shape: arm32.
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_ARM32 from MachineCode:
        Let arm32_out be proc generate_arm32_assembly from ARM32Gen with lir_module, backend_config
        Return arm32_out
    End If

    Note: Direct-shape: riscv (both 64- and 32-bit go through the
    Note: same generator; the backend_config carries the bit-width).
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_RISCV64 from MachineCode:
        Let riscv64_out be proc generate_riscv_assembly from RISCVGen with lir_module, backend_config
        Return riscv64_out
    End If
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_RISCV32 from MachineCode:
        Let riscv32_out be proc generate_riscv_assembly from RISCVGen with lir_module, backend_config
        Return riscv32_out
    End If

    Note: Context-shape backends below all need an AssemblyOutput
    Note: allocated up-front. Use the runtime allocator since these
    Note: are top-level emit buffers that need to outlive the
    Note: context-shape generators' internal lifetimes.
    Let asm_output be proc create_assembly_output from MachineCode with 0
    If asm_output is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Context-shape: mips (mips64 and mips32 share the entry).
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_MIPS64 from MachineCode:
        Let mips_ctx be proc create_mips_asm_context from MIPSGen with asm_output, backend_config
        If mips_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let mips_rc be proc generate_mips_assembly from MIPSGen with mips_ctx, lir_module
        If mips_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_MIPS32 from MachineCode:
        Let mips32_ctx be proc create_mips_asm_context from MIPSGen with asm_output, backend_config
        If mips32_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let mips32_rc be proc generate_mips_assembly from MIPSGen with mips32_ctx, lir_module
        If mips32_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If

    Note: Context-shape: powerpc.
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_POWERPC from MachineCode:
        Let ppc_ctx be proc create_ppc_asm_context from PPCGen with asm_output, backend_config
        If ppc_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let ppc_rc be proc generate_ppc_assembly from PPCGen with ppc_ctx, lir_module
        If ppc_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If

    Note: Context-shape: wasm (wasm32 and wasm64 share the entry).
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_WASM32 from MachineCode:
        Let wasm_ctx be proc create_wasm_asm_context from WasmGen with asm_output, backend_config
        If wasm_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let wasm_rc be proc generate_wasm_text from WasmGen with wasm_ctx, lir_module
        If wasm_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_WASM64 from MachineCode:
        Let wasm64_ctx be proc create_wasm_asm_context from WasmGen with asm_output, backend_config
        If wasm64_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let wasm64_rc be proc generate_wasm_text from WasmGen with wasm64_ctx, lir_module
        If wasm64_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If

    Note: Unknown architecture: defensive zero return. The validator
    Note: catches this by exit-code regression, but the function does
    Note: NOT alert here because the dispatcher is called inside
    Note: compile_program which has its own Phase 8 error path.
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: dispatch_binary_emit_by_arch -- LIR -> object-file binary emit
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Companion dispatcher to dispatch_codegen_by_arch. Where dispatch_codegen
produces target-specific assembly TEXT (consumed by an external assembler),
dispatch_binary_emit produces target-specific binary BYTES directly into a
caller-supplied output buffer. This is the entry point for the object-file
emit path used by:

  1. The eventual -c flag (compile to object without invoking assembler).
  2. The AOTT runtime when it wants in-process binary patching.
  3. The binary_emit_smoke test caller authored by D9 (which exercises this
     dispatcher end-to-end against a trivial LIR module).

Per CEO Q1 ratification: PE and Mach-O object format writers must be wired
NOW (not @Reserved_For). This dispatcher does not select the object FORMAT
(that is dispatch_object_format_by_os) -- it selects the architecture-
specific INSTRUCTION ENCODER. The two dispatchers compose: arch encoder
fills the .text section; object-format writer wraps that text section in
the ELF/PE/Mach-O scaffolding.

For arches whose module-level binary entry point is not yet authored
(MIPS/PPC/RISC-V/x86 -- their instruction_encoder.runa files contain
per-opcode encode_* procs but no encode_*_lir_module aggregator), this
dispatcher returns -1 with a single Alert; the audit's @Reserved_For
escape hatch is forbidden by the CEO no-defer directive, so those arches
must produce a real -1 (caller-visible failure) rather than silent 0.
The v0.0.8.5 supported binary-emit arches are x86_64 (encode_lir_module)
and wasm32/wasm64 (encode_module).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Branch on target_arch identical in structure to dispatch_codegen_by_arch.
For x86_64, call encode_lir_module(output, module_ptr) which lives in
x86_64/instruction_encoder.runa.
For wasm32/wasm64, the WASM encoder operates on a WasmModuleState that
has been pre-populated by the LIR-to-WAT path; the binary-emit path here
expects the caller to pass that already-populated state as the module_ptr.
Return value: number of bytes emitted (positive), or -1 on error.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Branch overhead identical to dispatch_codegen_by_arch (single integer
compare-and-branch). The work happens inside the per-arch encoder.
Called once per object-file emit (i.e., never on the hot compile path of
v0.0.8.5; binary emit is reserved for explicit driver flags or AOTT).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Output buffer is caller-supplied; this dispatcher does not allocate.
Per-arch encoders are responsible for bounds checks against the output
buffer's capacity. Returning -1 on unsupported arch surfaces failure
explicitly rather than risking a silent zero-byte object file.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "dispatch_binary_emit_by_arch" that takes target_arch as Integer, lir_module as Integer, output_buffer as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_module is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If output_buffer is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: x86_64 binary emit -- production path.
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_X86_64 from MachineCode:
        Let x86_emit_size be proc encode_lir_module from X86Encoder with output_buffer, lir_module
        Return x86_emit_size
    End If

    Note: wasm32 / wasm64 binary emit. The wasm encoder consumes a
    Note: WasmModuleState (populated upstream by the LIR-to-WAT
    Note: build), not a raw LIRModule. Caller passes the state as
    Note: lir_module argument.
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_WASM32 from MachineCode:
        Let wasm32_emit_size be proc encode_module from WasmEncoder with lir_module
        Return wasm32_emit_size
    End If
    If target_arch is equal to TARGET_ARCH_WASM64 from MachineCode:
        Let wasm64_emit_size be proc encode_module from WasmEncoder with lir_module
        Return wasm64_emit_size
    End If

    Note: Other arches have per-opcode encoders but no module-level
    Note: aggregator yet. Surface the unsupported case explicitly
    Note: rather than silently emitting a zero-byte object file.
    Alert "[BINARY EMIT] dispatch_binary_emit_by_arch: arch not wired"
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: dispatch_object_format_by_os -- OS -> ELF/PE/Mach-O selection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Selects the object-file FORMAT (envelope) based on the target OS. The
format wraps the binary code produced by dispatch_binary_emit_by_arch
in the platform-native executable container:

  ELF64   - Linux, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD (System V ABI)
  PE      - Windows (Portable Executable)
  Mach-O  - macOS / Darwin
  raw     - WASI / bare-metal (no envelope; binary is the WASM .wasm)

Per CEO Q1 ratification (override architect default @Reserved_For):
PE and Mach-O ARE wired here in v0.0.8.5. They are not AOTT-exempt and
must be reachable from the driver. Calling create_pe_builder,
pe_build_executable, pe_get_output_buffer / create_macho_builder,
macho_build_executable, macho_get_output_buffer makes the seven PE/Mach-O
"orphan" Processes reachable.

This dispatcher returns a builder pointer (per format type). The caller
extracts the final byte buffer via the format-specific get_output_buffer
function. The two-step design lets the caller decide whether to inspect,
patch, or write the buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Map OS code to format: Linux/BSDs -> ELF, Windows -> PE,
   Darwin -> Mach-O, WASI -> raw (returns the binary buffer directly).
2. Create the format-specific builder (image base / CPU type fixed
   defaults: ELF64 base 0x400000, PE image base 0x140000000, Mach-O
   cpu_type 16777223 = CPU_TYPE_X86_64).
3. Invoke the format's build_executable with the code buffer
   produced upstream by dispatch_binary_emit_by_arch.
4. Return the builder pointer (caller drains via *_get_output_buffer
   and *_get_output_size).

Returns 0 on error.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Three-way branch on OS code. Builders are heap-allocated once per
object-file emit. Mach-O builder is the heaviest (universal-binary
support adds load-command bookkeeping); ELF64 is the lightest.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. Builder allocations live for the lifetime of the
object-file emit. Caller must call the format-specific *_destroy_builder
function (or rely on arena teardown).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "dispatch_object_format_by_os" that takes target_os as Integer, code_buffer as Integer, code_size as Integer, data_buffer as Integer, data_size as Integer, rodata_buffer as Integer, rodata_size as Integer returns Integer:
    If code_buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If code_size is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: ELF64 path -- Linux, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD.
    If target_os is equal to TARGET_OS_LINUX from MachineCode:
        Let elf_builder be proc create_elf64_builder from ExecFormat with 4194304
        If elf_builder is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let elf_rc be proc elf64_build_executable from ExecFormat with elf_builder, code_buffer, code_size, data_buffer, data_size, rodata_buffer, rodata_size
        If elf_rc is equal to 0:
            proc elf64_destroy_builder from ExecFormat with elf_builder
            Return 0
        End If
        proc elf64_finalize from ExecFormat with elf_builder
        Return elf_builder
    End If
    If target_os is equal to TARGET_OS_FREEBSD from MachineCode:
        Let elf_bsd_builder be proc create_elf64_builder from ExecFormat with 4194304
        If elf_bsd_builder is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let elf_bsd_rc be proc elf64_build_executable from ExecFormat with elf_bsd_builder, code_buffer, code_size, data_buffer, data_size, rodata_buffer, rodata_size
        If elf_bsd_rc is equal to 0:
            proc elf64_destroy_builder from ExecFormat with elf_bsd_builder
            Return 0
        End If
        proc elf64_finalize from ExecFormat with elf_bsd_builder
        Return elf_bsd_builder
    End If
    If target_os is equal to TARGET_OS_OPENBSD from MachineCode:
        Let elf_openbsd_builder be proc create_elf64_builder from ExecFormat with 4194304
        If elf_openbsd_builder is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let elf_openbsd_rc be proc elf64_build_executable from ExecFormat with elf_openbsd_builder, code_buffer, code_size, data_buffer, data_size, rodata_buffer, rodata_size
        If elf_openbsd_rc is equal to 0:
            proc elf64_destroy_builder from ExecFormat with elf_openbsd_builder
            Return 0
        End If
        proc elf64_finalize from ExecFormat with elf_openbsd_builder
        Return elf_openbsd_builder
    End If
    If target_os is equal to TARGET_OS_NETBSD from MachineCode:
        Let elf_netbsd_builder be proc create_elf64_builder from ExecFormat with 4194304
        If elf_netbsd_builder is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let elf_netbsd_rc be proc elf64_build_executable from ExecFormat with elf_netbsd_builder, code_buffer, code_size, data_buffer, data_size, rodata_buffer, rodata_size
        If elf_netbsd_rc is equal to 0:
            proc elf64_destroy_builder from ExecFormat with elf_netbsd_builder
            Return 0
        End If
        proc elf64_finalize from ExecFormat with elf_netbsd_builder
        Return elf_netbsd_builder
    End If

    Note: PE path -- Windows.
    If target_os is equal to TARGET_OS_WINDOWS from MachineCode:
        Let pe_builder be proc create_pe_builder from ExecFormat with 5368709120
        If pe_builder is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let pe_rc be proc pe_build_executable from ExecFormat with pe_builder, code_buffer, code_size, data_buffer, data_size, rodata_buffer, rodata_size
        If pe_rc is equal to 0:
            proc pe_destroy_builder from ExecFormat with pe_builder
            Return 0
        End If
        Return pe_builder
    End If

    Note: Mach-O path -- Darwin / macOS / iOS.
    If target_os is equal to TARGET_OS_DARWIN from MachineCode:
        Note: cpu_type 16777223 = CPU_TYPE_X86_64 (0x01000007).
        Let macho_builder be proc create_macho_builder from ExecFormat with 16777223
        If macho_builder is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let macho_rc be proc macho_build_executable from ExecFormat with macho_builder, code_buffer, code_size, data_buffer, data_size, rodata_buffer, rodata_size
        If macho_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return macho_builder
    End If

    Note: WASI / bare-metal -- no object envelope. The wasm32/64
    Note: binary is the .wasm file directly.
    If target_os is equal to TARGET_OS_WASI from MachineCode:
        Return code_buffer
    End If
    If target_os is equal to TARGET_OS_BARE_METAL from MachineCode:
        Return code_buffer
    End If

    Note: Unknown OS -- defensive zero.
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: compile_program -- THE 11-PHASE PIPELINE
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "compile_program" that takes program as Integer, output_path as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Per-file compile orchestrator. Consumes the imports-merged AST
    and emits a target assembly file at output_path. P1-E v3 authors
    this body in the same commit as Layer 1 (WPA internals) and
    Layer 2 (optimize_program glue) per CEO directive against orphan
    code shipment.

    Pipeline:
        AST -> HIR -> MIR -> optimize_program(WPA + per-function)
            -> LIR -> instruction_select -> register_allocate
            -> peephole -> generate_{arch}_assembly -> asm_finalize
            -> write_file

    Returns 0 on success, nonzero on hard error.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Eleven phases, each with single failure exit. Per-job arena owns
    transient IRs and codegen workspace; arena_destroy at end
    releases them all in O(1). Optimization level read from
    BuildContext via get_active_opt_level with BUILD_OPT_BASIC
    fallback for the legacy single-file driver path.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Critical-path Process; called once per source file across full
    builds. Arena allocation pattern keeps per-compile-job allocator
    cost amortized across thousands of small temps. WPA pipeline
    gated to >= O2 inside optimize_program.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Reads source-derived AST, emits assembly text
    to a caller-supplied path. write_file's path validation is the
    security boundary; this Process does not touch network,
    environment, or processes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Phase 0 -- argument validation.
    If program is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: null program AST"
        Return 1
    End If
    If output_path is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: null output_path"
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 1 -- arena bootstrap + opt_level resolution.
    Let arena be proc arena_create from Layout with COMPILE_JOB_ARENA_INITIAL
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: arena allocation failed"
        Return 1
    End If
    Let opt_level be get_active_opt_level()

    Note: Phase 2 -- source-file tagging.
    Let main_input_name be derive_input_name_from_output(output_path, arena)
    If main_input_name is not equal to 0:
        tag_source_files_in_program(program, main_input_name)
    End If

    Note: Phase 3 -- AST to HIR lowering.
    Let hir_program be proc lower_ast_to_hir from HIRBuilder with program
    If hir_program is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: HIR lowering failed"
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 3a -- FFI library collection (D-FFI-09).
    Note: Walk the HIR program for HIR_EXTERNAL_DECLARATION nodes and register
    Note: each library_name with the FFI library collector for link-time use.
    Note: Also captures the active target OS for the link helpers below.
    Set ffi_target_os_active to get_target_os_from_config()
    ffi_scan_hir_program_for_externals(hir_program)

    Note: Phase 4 -- HIR to MIR lowering (P2-E v3 visitor-driven).
    Note: Public entry point lives in compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/lowering/definition_lowering.runa
    Let mir_program be proc lower_hir_program from DefLowering with hir_program
    If mir_program is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: MIR construction failed"
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 5 -- optimize_program (the P1-E hook).
    Note: Layer 2 contract: returns 0 on success, nonzero on failure.
    Note: At opt_level=0 (O0) the call is a no-op fast path.
    Let opt_result be proc optimize_program from Optimization with mir_program, opt_level
    If opt_result is not equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: optimize_program failed"
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 6 -- MIR to LIR lowering.
    Let target_os be get_target_os_from_config()
    Let target_arch be get_target_arch_from_config()
    Let calling_convention be proc create_convention_for_target from X86CallConv with target_os
    If calling_convention is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: calling convention creation failed"
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
        Return 1
    End If
    Let lir_module be proc build_lir_module_from_mir from LIRBuilder with mir_program, calling_convention
    If lir_module is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: LIR lowering failed"
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 7 -- per-LIR-function passes.
    Note: 7a: instruction selection.
    Note: 7b: register allocation (build interference graph then allocate).
    Note: 7c: peephole optimizations (gated >= BUILD_OPT_BASIC).
    Note: External (declaration-only) functions skip all three passes.
    Note: The LIRModule struct (lir_create_module) stores its functions
    Note: List at offset 8; iterate over that List, not the module struct.
    Let lir_functions be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with lir_module, 8
    Let lir_func_count be 0
    If lir_functions is not equal to 0:
        Set lir_func_count to proc list_length from List with lir_functions
    End If
    Let fi be 0
    While fi is less than lir_func_count:
        Let lir_func be proc list_get from List with lir_functions, fi
        If lir_func is not equal to 0:
            Let is_external be __load(lir_func, 112)
            If is_external is equal to 0:
                proc select_instructions from InstrSelect with lir_func
                Note: 7b: register allocation.
                Note: build_interference_graph runs liveness internally; the
                Note: allocation context exposes allocation@24 and
                Note: spill_worklist@40. A non-empty spill worklist means the
                Note: select phase could not color every value with the
                Note: available physical registers; we must insert spill
                Note: stores/reloads (spilling.insert_spill_code), rebuild
                Note: liveness + interference, and re-run allocation until the
                Note: worklist drains (convergence is guaranteed because each
                Note: spilled value's live range is shortened to single
                Note: def/use slices). Only then do we verify the map covers
                Note: every referenced virtual register and apply it in place,
                Note: rewriting virtual register ids to physical ids in the
                Note: shared operand records. allocate_registers returns 0 on
                Note: internal failure; apply_allocation/verify_allocation
                Note: return 0 on failure -- the x86_64 backend treats a stray
                Note: virtual register as fatal, so any failure here aborts the
                Note: compile rather than emitting garbage.
                Let ig be proc build_interference_graph from Interference with lir_func
                If ig is equal to 0:
                    Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: interference graph construction failed"
                    proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
                    Return 1
                End If

                Let context be proc allocate_registers from RegisterAlloc with lir_func, ig
                If context is equal to 0:
                    Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: register allocation failed"
                    proc destroy_interference_graph from Interference with ig
                    proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
                    Return 1
                End If

                Let spill_worklist be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with context, 40
                Let spill_count be proc list_length from List with spill_worklist
                Let regalloc_failed be 0
                Let spill_rounds be 0
                While spill_count is greater than 0:
                    Set spill_rounds to spill_rounds plus 1
                    If spill_rounds is greater than 64:
                        Note: Convergence guard: each round strictly shortens
                        Note: live ranges, so a real allocator converges far
                        Note: below this bound; exceeding it signals a defect.
                        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: register allocation did not converge"
                        Set regalloc_failed to 1
                        Set spill_count to 0
                    Otherwise:
                        Let spill_ok be proc insert_spill_code from Spilling with lir_func, spill_worklist
                        If spill_ok is equal to 0:
                            Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: spill code insertion failed"
                            Set regalloc_failed to 1
                            Set spill_count to 0
                        Otherwise:
                            Note: The program changed: rebuild liveness, graph, allocation.
                            Let liveness_ok be proc compute_function_liveness from Liveness with lir_func
                            If liveness_ok is equal to 0:
                                Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: post-spill liveness failed"
                                Set regalloc_failed to 1
                                Set spill_count to 0
                            Otherwise:
                                proc destroy_interference_graph from Interference with ig
                                Set ig to proc build_interference_graph from Interference with lir_func
                                If ig is equal to 0:
                                    Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: post-spill interference graph construction failed"
                                    Set regalloc_failed to 1
                                    Set spill_count to 0
                                Otherwise:
                                    Set context to proc allocate_registers from RegisterAlloc with lir_func, ig
                                    If context is equal to 0:
                                        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: post-spill register allocation failed"
                                        Set regalloc_failed to 1
                                        Set spill_count to 0
                                    Otherwise:
                                        Set spill_worklist to proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with context, 40
                                        Set spill_count to proc list_length from List with spill_worklist
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End While

                If regalloc_failed is not equal to 0:
                    If ig is not equal to 0:
                        proc destroy_interference_graph from Interference with ig
                    End If
                    proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
                    Return 1
                End If

                Note: Allocation converged: verify the map covers every
                Note: referenced virtual register and that no interfering
                Note: values share a physical register, then rewrite operands.
                Let allocation be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with context, 24
                Let valid be proc verify_allocation from RegisterAlloc with lir_func, allocation, ig
                If valid is equal to 0:
                    Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: register allocation verification failed"
                    proc destroy_interference_graph from Interference with ig
                    proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
                    Return 1
                End If

                Let apply_ok be proc apply_allocation from RegisterAlloc with lir_func, allocation
                If apply_ok is equal to 0:
                    Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: register allocation apply failed"
                    proc destroy_interference_graph from Interference with ig
                    proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
                    Return 1
                End If

                proc destroy_interference_graph from Interference with ig
                If opt_level is greater than or equal to BUILD_OPT_BASIC:
                    proc optimize_peephole from Peephole with lir_func
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set fi to fi plus 1
    End While

    Note: Phase 8 -- LIR to assembly text.
    Let backend_config be proc create_backend_config from MachineCode with target_arch, target_os, opt_level
    If backend_config is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: backend config creation failed"
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
        Return 1
    End If

    Let asm_output be dispatch_codegen_by_arch(target_arch, lir_module, backend_config)
    If asm_output is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: codegen failed"
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
        Return 1
    End If

    Let assembly_text be proc asm_finalize from MachineCode with asm_output, backend_config
    If assembly_text is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: assembly finalization failed"
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 9 -- write assembly to output_path.
    Note: write_file C-convention: 0 on success, nonzero on failure.
    Let write_result be proc write_file from FileOps with output_path, assembly_text
    If write_result is not equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: write_file failed"
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 10 -- teardown.
    Note: Arena bulk release: HIR module + MIR module + LIR module
    Note: + calling_convention + backend_config + asm_output text are
    Note: all released in O(1).
    proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
    Return 0
End Process
